items.scenario:
At 18:03:47 UTC on the 30th of the month, PagerDuty fires: 'checkout-api-prod RDSProxy/ConnectionBorrowTimeout 284/min (threshold: 10/min)'. Your multi-tenant SaaS checkout service runs on Node.js 20 Lambda functions (us-east-1, max concurrency: 1,000) connecting through RDS Proxy (checkout-db-proxy, Aurora PostgreSQL 15.4, db.r6g.large, max_connections: 400, MaxConnectionsPercent: 100). End-of-month billing jobs fire at 18:00 UTC, triggering concurrent Lambda invocations across 612 tenants.

Lambda error logs (CloudWatch Logs /aws/lambda/checkout-api-prod):

  2026-06-30T18:03:52.441Z ERROR [checkout-api] Failed to acquire database connection
    Error: TimeoutError: timeout exceeded when trying to connect
      at Pool.<anonymous> (/var/task/node_modules/pg-pool/index.js:256:13)
    { requestId: 'a8f3c2d1-4e5b-4c6a-b7d8-9e0f1a2b3c4d', tenantId: 'tenant-acme-corp',
      proxyEndpoint: 'checkout-db-proxy.proxy-c8xk9vwq.us-east-1.rds.amazonaws.com:5432' }
  [repeating for 71.4% of Lambda invocations from 18:03:47 to 18:22:15 UTC]

CloudWatch RDS Proxy metrics (18:00–18:25 UTC):
  RDSProxy/DatabaseConnections:       400/400 (at cap for 19 minutes)
  RDSProxy/ClientConnections:         612
  RDSProxy/ConnectionBorrowTimeout:   284 errors/min (peak)
  RDSProxy/QueryRequests:             0 (zero new queries proceeding at peak)
  Aurora/CPUUtilization:              8% (Aurora is healthy and idle)
  Aurora/DatabaseConnections:         400 (receiving nothing new)

db.js connection setup code (deployed 7 months prior without review):

  const { Pool } = require('pg');
  function createPool(tenantId) {
    const pool = new Pool({
      connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL,  // points to RDS Proxy
      max: 1,
      idleTimeoutMillis: 300000,  // 5 minutes — default, never tuned for Lambda
    });
    pool.on('connect', async (client) => {
      await client.query(`SET search_path TO tenant_${tenantId}, public`);
    });
    return pool;
  }

RDS Proxy logs (CloudWatch Logs /aws/rds/proxy/checkout-db-proxy):

  2026-06-30T18:01:07.113Z [INFO] Pinned the connection to the session because of a change in session
    state. (context: SET search_path TO tenant_stripe-corp, public; session pinned by SET command)
  2026-06-30T18:01:07.114Z [INFO] Pinned the connection to the session ...
    (context: SET search_path TO tenant_acme-corp, public; session pinned by SET command)
  [400 identical 'session pinned by SET command' lines from 18:01:07 to 18:03:44 UTC]
  2026-06-30T18:03:46.772Z [ERROR] Connection limit reached: proxy checkout-db-proxy has 400/400
    connections in use. New connection requests will wait until a connection becomes available.
  [284 ConnectionBorrowTimeout events/min from 18:03:47 until 18:22:15 UTC]

Root cause: AWS RDS Proxy multiplexes Lambda connections onto a shared pool of backend PostgreSQL connections, enabling N:1 connection reuse. However, when RDS Proxy detects a `SET` statement, it enters pinned mode for that connection — the backend PostgreSQL connection is bound exclusively to that Lambda execution context for the remainder of its idle timeout (300 seconds, matching idleTimeoutMillis), and cannot be reused by any other invocation. This converts RDS Proxy from a connection multiplexer back to a 1:1 passthrough.

Normal operation (50 concurrent Lambdas): 50 pinned connections well within the 400 cap — no issue for 7 months. End-of-month billing run (612 concurrent Lambdas): Lambda 1–400 succeed. Lambdas 401–612 find all 400 proxy connections pinned — many by completed Lambda invocations whose contexts are warm but idle, holding pinned connections for 5 more minutes. 212 Lambdas hit ConnectionBorrowTimeout. 71.4% of billing jobs fail.

Business impact: End-of-month invoices not generated for 8 enterprise customers over 19 minutes. $3.2M in monthly billing not processed on schedule. $240K SLA credit exposure. Billing batch re-run required at 08:00 next business day, delaying accounts-receivable reconciliation by 14 hours.

items.exercise:
1. Triage — confirm pinning vs Aurora failure: CloudWatch → Aurora CPUUtilization = 8%, DatabaseConnections = 400 but QueryRequests ≈ 0 — Aurora is healthy and idle. The bottleneck is at the proxy layer. Open RDS Proxy logs: CloudWatch Logs → /aws/rds/proxy/checkout-db-proxy → filter 'session pinned'. Expect to see exactly 400 'session pinned by SET command' entries immediately preceding the ConnectionBorrowTimeout storm. This confirms root cause: SET search_path in the pg pool.on('connect') handler pins every connection. Cross-check: CloudWatch RDSProxy/DatabaseConnectionsSetupFailed = 0 (connections open fine), RDSProxy/DatabaseConnections = 400/400 (all in pinned state, no multiplexing occurring). Aurora never receives new queries because no connections are available to route them through.
2. Immediate relief — reduce pin duration and throttle billing concurrency: (a) Throttle billing Lambda concurrency to 50 via Lambda console → checkout-api-billing → Configuration → Concurrency → Reserved = 50. This allows queued invocations to proceed as the 400 pinned connections time out over the next 5 minutes (idleTimeoutMillis=300s). (b) Reduce RDS Proxy ClientConnectTimeout from default 120s to 10s to fail fast and return errors to callers instead of blocking: `aws rds modify-db-proxy --db-proxy-name checkout-db-proxy --idle-client-timeout 10`. (c) Monitor RDSProxy/DatabaseConnections — expect it to start dropping from 400 as 5-minute pin timeouts expire starting at 18:06. By 18:10, DatabaseConnections should be below 200 and error rate should clear.
3. Root fix — replace SET with a PostgreSQL connection startup parameter: PostgreSQL accepts session configuration via the `options` connection string parameter (RFC 3986 encoded). Startup parameters are processed during the connection handshake before the session is handed to the client application. RDS Proxy treats these as part of connection identity, not session state changes, and does NOT pin connections for them. Code fix in db.js:

  function createPool(tenantId) {
    const encodedSchema = encodeURIComponent(`-csearch_path=tenant_${tenantId},public`);
    const pool = new Pool({
      connectionString: `${process.env.DATABASE_URL}?options=${encodedSchema}`,
      max: 1,
      idleTimeoutMillis: 30000,  // 30s — Lambda contexts are ephemeral
    });
    // Remove pool.on('connect') handler entirely — no SET commands
    return pool;
  }

4. Validate no pinning after deploy: run a load test simulating 612 concurrent Lambdas against the staging RDS Proxy (same db.r6g.large instance class, same max_connections=400): `k6 run --vus 612 --duration 60s billing_load_test.js`. After fix: 0% ConnectionBorrowTimeout. CloudWatch RDSProxy/ClientConnections = 612, DatabaseConnections = 8–15 (50:1 multiplexing ratio confirms pinning eliminated). Verify staging RDS Proxy logs contain zero 'session pinned' entries during the 60-second test window. Promote to production.
5. Tune idleTimeoutMillis for Lambda lifecycle: Lambda execution contexts are reused but eventually recycled. With idleTimeoutMillis=300s, a warmed Lambda holds a proxy connection for 5 minutes after its last query. At 400 max_connections and any significant idle Lambda fleet, this consumes the connection cap on idle contexts. Set idleTimeoutMillis=30000 (30s) — connections are released quickly when Lambda scales down or idles. This also eliminates the idle-hold contribution to the pinning storm independently of the SET fix.
6. Prevent: (a) Add CloudWatch alarm: RDSProxy/ConnectionBorrowTimeout > 10 per minute for 2 consecutive periods → PagerDuty P2 'RDS Proxy connection pool exhausted'. This fires 3 minutes into the pinning storm, enabling preemptive throttling. (b) Add RDS Proxy pinning detection alarm: CloudWatch Metric Filter on /aws/rds/proxy/checkout-db-proxy matching 'session pinned by SET command' > 20 times in 5 minutes → PagerDuty P2. Would have fired at 18:01:30, 2 minutes before the storm began. (c) Add CI integration test: create a test pool against a staging proxy, issue `SET application_name='test'`, assert RDSProxy/DatabaseConnections = RDSProxy/ClientConnections (1:1 ratio = pinned) → fail the build with a link to the RDS Proxy pinning documentation. (d) Add ADR entry for all Lambda+RDS Proxy services: 'Never issue SET statements in pg pool connect handlers or connection setup code. Use connection string options= startup parameters for session configuration. Allowed: search_path, TimeZone, statement_timeout. Forbidden: pool.on(connect) SET commands.' (e) Set RDS Proxy MaxConnectionsPercent=50 (200 connections) during non-billing hours via a scheduled Lambda (EventBridge), scaling to 100% only at billing run time — limits blast radius of future pinning events to 200-connection ceiling during off-peak.

1. Diagnose — pivot from model quality to infrastructure by correlating duration clustering: Query X-Ray: `aws xray get-service-graph --start-time 1750330800 --end-time 1750341600 | jq '.Services[] | select(.Name=="bedrock") | .Edges[].SummaryStatistics'` — reveals 847 traces with Duration in tight band 60.8–61.4s. Legitimate streaming durations would span 20–108s. The cluster at exactly 60s is the ALB idle timeout fingerprint. Confirm: `aws cloudwatch get-metric-statistics --namespace AWS/ApplicationELB --metric-name TargetConnectionErrorCount --period 300 --statistics Sum --start-time 2026-06-22T09:00:00Z --end-time 2026-06-22T13:00:00Z` — returns spike of 847 at 09:14 UTC. This metric is not alarmed: add it immediately as P2 (`TargetConnectionErrorCount > 10 per 5min`). Cross-check ALB attribute: `aws elbv2 describe-load-balancer-attributes --load-balancer-arn <arn> | jq '.Attributes[] | select(.Key=="idle_timeout.timeout_seconds")'` → `"Value": "60"`. Root cause confirmed: ALB drops 60s-idle connections, Go SDK misreads FIN as clean stream-end, partial buffer returned as HTTP 200.
2. Immediate hotfix — increase ALB idle timeout: `aws elbv2 modify-load-balancer-attributes --load-balancer-arn <arn> --attributes Key=idle_timeout.timeout_seconds,Value=300`. Takes effect within 60 seconds with zero downtime. Set to 5× the expected P99 stream duration (108s × 2.5 = 270s, rounded to 300s). Test: submit a 500-page M&A due-diligence checklist contract and confirm full 6,200-token response arrives in ~94s without truncation. Verify in X-Ray: trace duration now spreads across 20–108s range with no clustering at 60s.
3. Fix silent truncation — distinguish clean stream-end from abrupt FIN in Go handler: AWS Bedrock `MessageStreamEvent` includes a `MessageStopEvent` as the final event, containing `usage.output_tokens` (total tokens generated). After the stream loop exits, compare `receivedTokens` against `stopEvent.Usage.OutputTokens`. If the `MessageStopEvent` was never received (stream was cut by ALB FIN before final event), the handler must detect the missing stop event:
```go
var gotStopEvent bool
for event := range stream.Events() {
    switch v := event.(type) {
    case *types.ContentBlockDeltaEvent:
        buf.Write([]byte(v.Delta.Text))
    case *types.MessageStopEvent:
        gotStopEvent = true
        if v.Usage.OutputTokens > 0 && receivedTokens < int(v.Usage.OutputTokens)*9/10 {
            // Partial response — return error for retry
            w.WriteHeader(http.StatusServiceUnavailable)
            json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(map[string]string{"error": "stream_truncated", "received_tokens": strconv.Itoa(receivedTokens)})
            return
        }
    }
}
if !gotStopEvent {
    // ALB/network cut stream before Bedrock sent MessageStopEvent
    w.WriteHeader(http.StatusServiceUnavailable)
    json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(map[string]string{"error": "stream_terminated_early"})
    return
}
```
This converts silent data corruption into a 503 that triggers client-side retry and CloudWatch error-rate alerting. Deploy without downtime via rolling restart.
4. Fix root cause — enable true streaming (flush each chunk to client): The Go handler's buffer-then-send pattern is the proximate cause of ALB seeing 60s of silence. Switch to pass-through streaming: flush each SSE chunk immediately to the HTTP response writer as it arrives from Bedrock. This ensures bytes flow through the ALB connection continuously, preventing idle timeout regardless of `idle_timeout` setting:
```go
flusher := w.(http.Flusher)
for event := range stream.Events() {
    if delta, ok := event.(*types.ContentBlockDeltaEvent); ok {
        fmt.Fprintf(w, "data: %s\n\n", delta.Delta.Text)
        flusher.Flush()   // ← sends bytes to ALB immediately
    }
}
```
This is the defense-in-depth fix: even if `idle_timeout` is misconfigured in the future, the ALB never idles because tokens flow continuously.
5. Validate — multi-signal confirmation after both fixes: (a) Submit 10 M&A contracts: confirm all receive `MessageStopEvent`, word counts in 5,800–6,600 range. (b) ALB CloudWatch: `TargetConnectionErrorCount` drops to 0 after fix #4 deploy. (c) Data quality Lambda: next hourly run shows `p50 = 5,920 words` (back in healthy range). (d) X-Ray duration distribution: no longer clusters at 60s; spreads across 22–108s as expected. (e) Error rate stays 0% for legitimate requests; truncated responses now surface as 503 and appear in `HTTPCode_Target_5XX_Count`.
6. Prevent: (a) Terraform: `resource "aws_lb" "contract_api" { idle_timeout = max(var.max_streaming_seconds * 2, 120) }` — parameterized, enforces minimum headroom. Add Terraform Sentinel policy: `alb_idle_timeout >= bedrock_max_expected_p99_stream_duration * 1.5` — fails plan if idle timeout is too low for the configured `max_tokens`. (b) Deployment gate: in the CI pipeline for model config changes (max_tokens bump), add a check that computes `expected_stream_duration = max_tokens / avg_tokens_per_second` and validates it against `alb_idle_timeout`. Gate the deploy if `expected_stream_duration * 1.5 > alb_idle_timeout`. (c) CloudWatch alarm: `TargetConnectionErrorCount > 10 per 5min` → PagerDuty P2 'ALB connection errors: possible streaming timeout or downstream saturation'. (d) Data quality Lambda: lower sampling rate to 10-minute intervals (currently 60-minute) and add P25 word-count check (`< 2000 words` → P1 'contract analysis output severely truncated').
